  "prompt": "What is the best way to use a simple past tense in a sentence?",
  "response": "The simple past tense is used to describe actions or events that were completed at a specific time in the past. To use it in a sentence, you typically follow this structure: subject + past tense verb + (optional) time expression.\n\n**Example:**\n- Subject: \"She\"\n- Past tense verb: \"baked\"\n- Time expression: \"yesterday\"\n\nCombining these elements, you get: **\"She baked a cake yesterday.\"**\n\nHere are a few more examples:\n1. \"They visited the museum last week.\"\n2. \"I watched a movie on Friday.\"\n3. \"He finished his homework before dinner.\"\n\nMake sure the verb is in its correct past tense form, which may involve changing its spelling or using an irregular verb form.",
